,Not Recommended,433380,22696764,"Posted: 28 April, 2016",all,äby,"I'll preface this review by saying that I love survival horror games. I've spent several thousands of hours playing and watching many games of the genre, including the Silent Hill, Resident Evil, Alone in the Dark and Fatal Frame series, so it goes without saying I have no problem with dated controls or graphics.I was really excited for Back in 1995, and I wanted to like it. I was practically waiting down to the hour for it to be out on Steam. I already knew it was going to be a short game, as stated in the info on steam: ""Approximate playtime is 2-3 hours"".First to put things straight, that approximation is VERY off. I completely finished everything the game had to offer in about 1.25 hours, this is INCLUDING a section that had no gameplay and was just a set of text commentary. I already expected the game to be short and wouldn't have had a problem with it were it not for my second problem with the game:Substance. The game lacks any real substance in terms of plot, story devices or a conclusion. Most of the game is spent plodding along following instructions and tidbits of newspaper clippings and notes which establish a hint at some sort of extra layer to the story that is never quite fulfilled. The living characters are basically props, they offer nothing to the story and have no characterisation or personality. Even the unvoiced protagonist has barely anything to offer. It's a shame because after thefalse endingthe game looked like it was going to take a turn for the interesting, before being cut short and ending the game (which by the way, is basically just developer commentary which while cool doesn't really make up for the lack of conclusion). This game really excels at getting your hopes up for some excitement, then letting you down abruptly.In terms of audio, I was pretty underwhelmed. There was very little sound in the game, no change of footsteps whatsoever no matter what ground you walk on. The music was, well, I at least enjoyed the opening track? A lot of the music I found to be honestly kinda jarring and not in a good way. Usually a focal point of survival horror games is the use of sound design in order to create tension, fear and a foreboding sense of danger, whereas in this game it was mostly just some noise in the background, bar a few encounters with enemies that triggered music.So how about as an actual game. Well, the enemies are laughably easy, there was perhaps ONE enemy out of I believe the four that exist in the game that was even slightly threatening, and even then I had no issue taking it down. The game throws ammunition at you, as well as health items (painkillers). I should note here that I used painkillersoncein the entire game, when I intentionally allowed an enemy to hurt me to see if they even could attack or were non-hostile. For the rest of the game I stacked up probably around 15 or 16 bottles of painkillers that went unused because I never was even touched by an enemy. This is another key focus in survival horror games, you're supposed to fear enemies, you're supposed to have a need to conserve ammo, fighting is supposed to be difficult and risky, not a cakewalk with no chance of dying. I feel like the game completely misses the point in this aspect. The other side of gameplay is made up by some ""puzzles"" that either flat out tell you the solution to them by examining notes, or involve just process of elimination. Figuring out how to progress for most of the game was simply a matter of walking around examining everything until you get the solution handed to you on a platter.I don't really want to comment on the graphics too much because one of the big appeals of this game was the graphic style, the outdated low detail polygonal models and areas. I actually liked this idea, I'm a big fan of lo-fi visuals and I think in horror games it can sometimes contribute to the experience to have limited graphics. What I will say is some of the graphics start to contort and stretch in strange ways some times which honestly looks horrid, I'm not even sure if this is intentional or not but it reminded me more of a weird emulator glitch rather than something on actual hardware of 1995.So in conclusion, while I see that the creator of this game wanted to make a homage to some of the classics of this era of gaming, I honestly think all they made was a mere collection of references to an era. The style was great, and as I stated before I really, really wanted to like it but it just simply offered very little as a gaming experience. If the aim was to make a small game that reminded people of the games they played in 1995, I feel like it fell flat. It missed the key things that made these games great: atmosphere, plot (good or bad), fear, and most importantly CLIMAX. All of those games had excitement, and genuine endings, conclusions to the gameplay. Back in 1995 offers only a trudging path of ambiguity and build-up. I don't usually judge games on playtime vs price, but more they experience they give, and I don't feel like this game had much to offer for the price to play it.Short version: Neat idea & style, executed poorly. Not worth the price it's set at."
