76561198029345622,Recommended,433380,23130397,"Posted: 21 May, 2016",all,dreamprobe,"I believe this project was primarily intended for a very specific audience: players with fond memories of 32-bit 3D games, who maintained a fondness for those rough, chunky polygon graphics well after the next wave of consoles arrived, and came to regard those limitations as having created a legitimate style all their own, no less valid than NES and SNES-style pixel art. I'm part of that group, though you may not be.Even if you are, you still may not ""get"" this game. It's totally a style-over-substance work, but it's somewhat excusable for how well it nails the look of those fully rendered Playstation 3D adventures, such as Silent Hill 1, Echo Night, Clock Tower: Ghost Head and Aconcagua. Even if it isn't comparable to the length or objective quality of those games. The characteristic ""texture warping"" of the PS1's 3D rendering is faithfully recreated: every surface seems to stretch and pulse with your every step, making the world feel much more dynamic and ominously unstable than it really is. Since its presence in this game is as a deliberate feature rather than an unintentional consequence of the hardware, the environments and camera angles are laid out to take maximum advantage of its effects.Unless you are playing on an actual CRT monitor, I definitely recommend leaving the noisy CRT filter on to experience the full effect, and it's necessary for one of the game's fourth wall-breaking tricks to work. While so many modern retrogaming throwbacks would obviously never be able to run on the hardware they attempt to pay homage to, practically nothing about this game's visual presentation is out of character with a Playstation, Saturn or 3DO release from 1995, and I find that quite appealing.Don't expect a great breadth or depth of content. I finished it in about two hours (counting offline play), there's only two ""puzzles"" that require any degree of thinking, and there's only one room in the game with enemies that might actually kill you. Resident Evil 2, this ain't. The ending is very inconclusive, and mainly serves as a sort of developer's commentary. Despite these huge flaws, I felt that Back in 1995 was a worthwhile jaunt through some attractive and faithfully presented retro-3D environments, with a few clever ""gotcha"" moments and a palpable foreboding atmosphere. The developer is going to patch in voice acting eventually; if it sounds anything like the accented deadpan narration in the second trailer, it should contribute further to the overall feel and sense of 32-bit-era authenticity.Cautiously recommended for a certain type of gamer. You probably already know if you'll consider it to have been worth your time and money or not. If nothing else, it's definitely better and less pretentious than most other indie ""walking simulators"" on Steam. Oh, and there is actually a deeper significance to the title, though like everything else in the story, it's never fully explained."
