76561197993591684,Recommended,433380,22860339,"Posted: 8 May, 2016",all,JesseMan,"I recommend this game, but for only a specific group of people.If you're a huge fan of classic survival horror, you'll be able to ride the nostalgia train to the end. But there are flaws: the game provides no challenge in combat or puzzles, the monster designs are uninspired, the story has clever moments, but ultimately falls flat, and there are bugs, from ugly clipping to terrible camera angles, that are NOT related to the dated source material they're trying to imitate.Overall, I wish they spent a few months to polish the game. Game design was definitely tighter than this back in 1995.Also, $12 for a $5 game? I haven't felt this ripped off since I paid $12 for a Chumbawumba CD."
,Recommended,433380,22716392,"Posted: 29 April, 2016",all,Dauen,"You can either watch it or read it!*SPOILERS*https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fh-5-rEfTUIBack In 1995 is a throwback to the survival horror classics of the 1990s - such as Resident Evil, Silent Hill, and Alone in the Dark.I was really hyped for about a month waiting for it to come out. I didn't realize at the time it was going to be a one-man dev team, literally as I was downloading it, I was reading around on the game itself and came across that bit of information and all my hype basically disintegrated.Having already, in my mind, dedicated the next two hours to old-school survival horror, I figured I'd give it a whirl.First, this game supports quite a variety of controllers, which is sweet because this could've completed contradicted the point to the entire game - ""an homage to 90's survival horror"".The game then next give your CRT Effect options to simulate the crappy tvs a lot of us in our mid twenties plus grew up with. At first I was going to skip this effect, but ultimately opted for the CRT without noise, as old televisions have given my headaches my entire life.You start off on the roof of a random building, gazing off in the distance, you play as Kent as he is trying to get to a distant tower for unknown reasons.As all 90s survival horror titles, health items and ammo are scattered through the entire world and you have unlimited inventory space.Now I'll admit, the first monsters I called the ""Mr. Hankeys"" the entire game because they literally look like a giant turd nuggets with arms. Which is pretty weird, but at the same time, I was infinitely relieved they didn't go with zombies. I've always a huge zombie fan in the 90s, but something about them wouldn't sit right in this game.The first monsters are generally pretty easy to dispose of, three hits with your melee is all it takes.After unlocking a door or two, you answer a telephone and pass out.You wake up to a doctor taking care of you. After of which, he sends you on a couple errands where you have to complete puzzles and flex your brain just a little bit to complete. Just a fair warning, this is classic survival horror, so not a lot of things are going to make logical sense.After a couple puzzles, some items scavenging, and finding your first gun, you find yourself at Central University Hospital.Heading to the cafeteria, the find the shotgun and when could maybe considered the first and only boss battle.Which, by the way, the briefcase here can only be opened when your find the note stating how to open it. I found the code first and got♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥when it wouldn't work. Make sure you go down the hallway across the hall on the left hand side of the screen, it's a little hidden.After a little site seeing, you get to the final area of the game. Which appears to be a luxury, rooftop penthouse. This is where things begin to fall in place. After finding a crank to open a drawer - yes, every survival horror game has to have a crank, somehow, somewhere, I don't make the rules, I do however fully except them - you start to find a lot of notes directed at your character Kent regarding his mental condition. Even going so far as to explain why there is no run option in the game. Kent's condition caused him to lose that ability as well as cognitive functions.His mental condition is so unstable, he believes he is still in the year 1995 - hence the title.When your reach your final destination, the tower in the distance. Kent decides he's had enough and chooses to end his suffering.Which not to take away from the seriousness of the story... but he was on rooftops the entire game... he could've just jumped from anywhere and it would've had the same effect.Some things I want to point out that I liked-Tank controllers were spot on-The monsters were original, the big one really reminded me of the final transformation of Berkin from Resident Evil 2.-The overall feel was definitely 90s survival horror-The save points were 90s computers-Glitches were almost nonexistent-Notes everywhere, just like Silent Hill and Resident EvilSomething I think need work-some of the rooms were just a little empty-I found a glitch that gave me unlimited shotgun ammo pickups, in the hospital if you go back to the rooftop and return to the room with the briefcase, the ammo will respawn.-Also a second glitch that I unlocked the ""finish the game"" and ""get flashlight"" achievements, but somehow not ""clear the first stage"", ""clear the opening sequence"", ""get the pipewrench"", ""get pistol"" that are all completed within the first 10 minutes of playing.-The enemies should be a little tougher, if you attack first, they'll stop moving and as long as your keep attacking you'll kill them.-For an oldschool survival horror, there's too many health items and too much ammo.-If there were to be a sequel, which I really hope there is, I'd recommend more story depth and more boss battles. The story worked just fine for this project.After the game was over, it did something I did not all expect. After what I thought were the credits, the game started over again without me doing anything. I retained all my weapons and items and figured, ""what the hell, lets run through it a little more"". Upon entering the room with the telephone, instead I found a flashlight. After thinking ""what kind of creepypasta♥♥♥♥♥♥is this?"" I turned it on and was met with some text, then the font changed to a modern style.Intrigued, I continued. I went back to the roof and there was a scaffolding that hadn't been there before. I then made my way rooftop to rooftop, each covering an area I'd already been to.You find various notes on your way back to the tower, each one seeming to refer more to real life than the situation in the game itself. To me, the entire game is merely a social commentary on retrogaming and those of us who simply can't let it go. Those of us w ho grasp to that nostalgia, that first love we all had. It was new to us, that's why it was so great. We were young and everything seemed to pop so much more. Then we grew up, less and less felt new to us, and that first love became a only a memory.Making my way to the end, this time taking only 5 minutes or so, you're met with the final text ""Am I no different than he, who spent 20 years running away? Aren't we the same? From now on, will I lead a meaningless life. Is there no way to reclaim my own life?""I feel like this is the developer saying, 20 years ago when we were young, the ones before us were attached to Atari games and Pac-man. They refused to move on no matter how much we tried to   convince them Playstation, Resident Evil and Metal Gear Solid were better. They stopped moving forward, as have we - and if we aren't moving forward, we aren't progressing. We can't change the way nostalgia makes us feel.Loved the game, hope there is a sequel or the dev makes another survival horror. Hell of an installment for, primarily, just one developer."
