76561198083068272,Not Recommended,433380,25778142,"Posted: 30 September, 2016",all,TheBeak,"I hate being blatantly insulting or contrary but this game is largely a crapper.  In it you play as Kent Crapsworth the 1st, a completely boring snoozefest of a character trying to reach some tower far off in the distance whilst attempting to regain his memory and find his daughter or something.  Literally, I don't need to give you any exposition because the character is mundane and the backstory I just regurgitated is about all you get throughout the whole darn thing.Back in 1995 is a noble attempt to go back to the days of old school Alone in the Dark, Silent Hill and Resident Evil.  It's heart is in the right place but all of its body parts are stitched together like Frankenstein.  My heart literally sank as I played; the whole affair not even taking a whole two hours to beat...with the secret portion of the game being counted into that playtime as well.Crapsworth's quest requires you storming through office buildings and rooftops in search of documents, notes, etc. that really don't say a darn thing interesting.  You'll get a whopping three weapons in order to combat and take on a series of brown bomber enemies including renegade Thanksgiving butterballs, stationary worm creatures culled from Tremors II:  Aftershocks, an embryo on stilts and a massive hulking fleshbeast (that looks much more threatening than he is).  In between these fights that offer no challenge you'll meet nondescript characters who push the story along as you collect massive amounts of healing items, an army surplus of bullets and pretty much everything else that negates the aspect of ""survival.""Surprisingly enough, the tank controls are quite responsive with even an automatic lock-on system making sure enemies eat every bit of hot lead you throw at them, althrough you can beat the whole game by swinging your pipe wrench a few times and running for the hills.  I chose to kill every single creature in order to get at least half of my money's worth out of this royal flush.  Toilet humor is not my forte but this game inspires it plentifully.When talking about graphics n' sound, well, let's change the subject!  Even the early AITD's looked far better than this and don't even get me started on the first Silent Hill.  The sound is also horrendous, sporting some of the worst music I've heard in a horror game coupled to tepid sound effects that perfectly match.  Again, I feel bad about walking all over this game but DO NOT buy it unless it's $5 or under (hopefully under).  $11.99 is an absolute travesty of a price to even ask for such a weak ""game.""  The developer's heart is in the right place, sure, yet this costs money and you can spend it far better elsewhere.  Despite negative reviews I went in with an open mind, even anticipating the fact that the developer is adding extra features which includes a hard mode but I uninstalled this after playing thorugh it once.  Hell, I got all of the achievements anyway.Pros:-Playable with no major glitches-Solid controls-At the core the developer tried to do the right thing with the game.Cons:-No challenge whatsoever.-No survival aspect.-Wretched graphics and sound even in the context of throwback standards.-Horribly short.-Overpriced.-No story, intrigue or mystique.Overall rating:  3/10Back in 1995 is only for the morbidly curious.  There's barely enough game here to call it a game I'm sorry to say.  Other than playing technically well, a surprise considering the rest of the content, there is nothing here that fits the title of survival horror.  I'm going to hang onto it because once the wounds heal I might give hard-mode a go, but players looking for a budget survival horror game with some actual meat on the bones would be much better off looking into 2nd/3rd tier games like Curse: Eye of Isis or Cold Fear (if they haven't played some of the more unknown titles) than this stodgy affair."
